A Czechman Referees the Struggle for the Seabed
It is approaching a wall-mounted electronic map, depicting Australia and adjacent marine areas.
However, he is not interested in the continent, but in a small point lost in the blue of the ocean.
"The island belongs to Australia, as does the adjacent seabed.
This area is as big as the continent itself,” said Italian lawyer Luigi Santosuosso, who is part of the 30-member team of the UN Oceans and Law of the Sea Division.
Its leader, the director of the division, the Czech jurist Václav Mikulka, follows the presentation and completes it from time to time.
The ardor at work and the enthusiasm characterize the prevailing atmosphere.
The seabed hides a little-known world, rich in natural resources.
There are petroleum, minerals and other mineral resources, but also currently unknown living organisms, which may hold the key to the development of a cancer drug.
A wider bottom than the hard land
Coastal states nowadays have begun to vehemently aspire to the new underwater territories.
According to a UN convention, they are indeed making use of their rights, on which they agreed in 1982 in Montego Bay, Jamaica.
This is mainly the area of what is called the continental shelf, which often extends several hundred kilometers from the coast of the given country.
The latter may, according to the Convention, exclusively claim all resources of the continental shelf.
To simplify, the continental shelf is considered the part of the seabed and its subsoil, which constitutes a natural extension of the continent under the sea.
It extends beyond the limits of the coastal sea, often also beyond the two hundred nautical miles that represent the so-called exclusive economic yone," Mikulka explains.
The country's request to the Commission for the establishment of the outer borders of the continental shelf must be supported by extensive scientific and technical documentation, based on many costly prospecting and metrics.
It is the result of several years of preparatory work.
"One of our roles is to provide the commission with legal and scientific-technical assistance.
To date, the Commission has dealt with five applications, including those from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
At the moment, only the last three countries mentioned have been successful,” adds Mikulka.
The success of Australia, which is the first to have significantly expanded its underwater possessions, has recently seen a global impact.
New Zealand, too, has gained territory - the extent of the seabed assigned to it by the commission last week corresponds to 1.6 million square kilometers, representing the extent of the country multiplied by six.
The two countries have invested millions of dollars in prospecting.
The future benefits they will derive from the exploitation of the seabed will be, as they project it, invaluable.
Progressively, other countries will, in turn, submit their requests.
They can do so within ten years of ratifying the “Montego Bay Convention.”
There, where the continental shelf ends, begins the zone of the ocean floor, proclaimed by convention "the common heritage of humanity".
There no longer does any state enjoy an exclusive position.
The right of extraction in this area is granted by an international institution established by convention.
"However, let's not be mistaken, the seabed is not a Klondike," said director Mikulka, exaggerating that "its areas are precisely clearly defined and their regime anchored in a contract."
Czechs in the Pacific
Part of the seabed now also belongs to the Czech Republic.
It shares it with other states of the former bloc of the Eastern countries within the framework of the joint organization "Interoceanmetal".
In 1991, it was granted the status of a so-called "pioneer investor" by the Convention, as well as investors from a few other States.
It has the right of extraction in the ClarionClipperton zone in the Pacific Ocean, located between Mexico, the Hawaii Islands and Kiribati.
The area prospected by the investor slightly exceeds the area of the former Czechoslovakia.
The bottom is turbulent, it is a kind of underwater replica of the Tatra.
"It is possible to extract it over an area with a total area of 75,000 square kilometers.
The area represents a deposit rich in polymetallic concretions containing nickel, copper, cobalt and manganese," says Ind Pakshi Rajan, another lawyer.
Rober Sandev, a Macedonian employee of the division, provides an example of such a concretion.
It is reminiscent of a small potato, or, with a little imagination, the mythical shoem, which, according to legend, animated the Golem.
