Morgan Stanley adopted the new status last week, which should allow it to diversify its business but put it under the authority of the Federal Reserve.
His alliance with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing the biggest names on Wall Street to adopt a much more cautious attitude than before.
The terms presented on Monday also show that the deal has been changed in the past few days: Last Monday, Morgan had simply announced that it would sell up to 20% of its shares to the Japanese for about $8.5 billion.
“A week ago,” Toshihide Mizuno, the executive director of MUFG, told Tokyo, “we thought the stake would be entirely made up of common shares.
But given the current state of the economy and the market, we wanted to minimize the risks and cover ourselves."
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will pay its Morgan Stanley securities 7% below their book value.
And the operation will result in a dilution of about 20% of profit per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferential securities into common stock within a year if the latter are traded more than 50% above the conversion price, i.e. at about $47, during a given period.
Morgan Stanley says the capital provided by MUFG will enable it to seize investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its liquidity.
A spokeswoman for the group, however, declined to elaborate on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
