Rafael Correa in Quito this Monday.
To refound the republic around the socialism of the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his counterparts and friends, was the third to put to the vote a draft new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since 64% of voters voted "yes" in the referendum, according to official results covering 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" obtained 28%, 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% were white votes.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to obtain half of the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls conducted outside the polling stations and a count of a non-governmental organization announced a wide victory of "yes", ranging between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had claimed the victory of his draft constitution in the night of Sunday to Monday.
The “Constitution triumphed overwhelmingly,” he said, congratulating Ecuadorians at the Guayaquil governorate headquarters, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which took place calmly according to the Organization of American States (OAS) observation mission, dealt with a 444-point text consolidating the "new socialism" defended by the president.
The draft constitution consecrates the power of the state over the economy, reserving to it the "planning of the development" of a country living mainly of the extraction of oil by foreign companies and the currencies sent by its emigrants.
Supported by Correa, elected in 2006, the draft also grants enhanced powers to the head of state, who will be able to hold up to two consecutive four-year terms and will have the opportunity to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and will run for a new term in February 2009.
The Constitution also consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the President has begun to introduce in this country of 13.9 million people, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It also foresees a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington to use an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for U.S. anti-drug operations.
The 19 hostages were freed in Chad.
An Egyptian commando has launched an assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions captured ten days ago.
They are in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions held captive for ten days in the desert were brought back safely to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they had been released by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
Apparently in shape, the hostages arrived at around 3.30 p.m. on a special aircraft at al-Maza military base, docked at Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred, without being able to speak to the press, by helicopter to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for examinations.
They are in “good health,” and “no ransom has been paid” to the kidnappers, Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna said on the tarmac.
Captured on September 19 during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the edge of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been tossed from one hiding place to the other by 35 unknown kidnappers.
It includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the agency Aegyptus, organizer of the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, transported aboard two helicopters, launched the assault in the night just before dawn.
"An exchange of gunshots occurred, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others fleeing," said the official who requested anonymity.
He said 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "lightning unit" had been sent to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
The head of Italian diplomacy Franco Frattini mentioned from Belgrade, where he is, the role played by secret agents and elements of the Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and effectiveness of our men of the secret services, special forces," he said, without further details.
He also denied paying a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted during a patrol a 4x4 vehicle on which the kidnappers were on board, killing six, including the Chadian leader, and arresting two.
The army had claimed that they were linked to a Darfur rebel group, the Sudan Unity Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which the movement immediately denied.
