Benelux Governments Nationalize Part of Fortis Bank
The Benelux states are helping the Belgian-Dutch bank, as the first European bank in distress following the snowball effect of the credit market crisis in the United States, by partially nationalising it. The three countries support, in the amount of 11.2 billion euros, this financial and insurance institution also owns interests in Hungary.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments agreed, at the highest level, on this matter, also appealing to the European Central Bank and the European Commission’s Competition Officer.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the international financial crisis, which has been widening for more than a year, is for Fortis Bank, and from a certain point of view, the decisions that will be taken in the case of this bank will serve as a precedent.
In line with the decision on Sunday night, the three states will buy back nearly half (to 49%) of the bank’s capital located in each of the countries.
The bank will undoubtedly sell part of its holdings, including, first and foremost, the insurance business, which it acquired last year from the Dutch company ABN Amro.
Last week, Fortis stocks began a dizzying decline, and in the second half of the week, serious signs of crisis have already been revealed at the bank.
Analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is far too big to go bankrupt.
On Friday alone, the company’s shares fell 12 percent to their lowest level 14 years ago.
Since January, stocks have fallen by more than two-thirds of their value.
Taking into account the current value of the shares, the total value of the group's capital is around 14 billion euros, which, according to the company's executives, is not realistic.
The company's management blames the uncertainty across the Atlantic, in connection with the adoption of the US bailout plan of $700 billion, to be the cause of the fall of the Fortis shares.
On Monday, papers have already benefited from a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the head of the bank, as the new CEO.
The financial institution was also looking for private buyers, but has not yet received a proposal on the merits.
Earlier, the Belgian government announced that investors should not worry, they would not lose their money.
No panic was felt in the bank's customer circle and no agencies were stormed.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent agencies and has also acquired leasing companies.
A fox in the chicken coop
In America, life and health insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate, based on information about his or her drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become out of control.
"There are data protection programmes that link the use of information regarding the prescription of medicines, in any case, with the consent of the data subject.
This kind of program must be in independent hands, otherwise it amounts to entrusting his henhouse to a fox," Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage prescription drugs, told the Washington Post.
Insurance companies depend on the insurance premium and the insured capital in the event of damage, on the state of health of the client that occurs, and if they feel that the risk is too great, they do not even insure it.
In the past, they sent the candidates for a medical examination, and they did not sign an insurance contract with them until they became aware of the results.
For the past ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, it is easily provided from pharmacies, data about the person's drug purchases in the past eighteen months. From this, the program determines itself, what disease the person suffers from and what is his health condition.
For example, if that person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol-lowering, this refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately puts them in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some determine a risk factor at the same time, so there is not much left to do for the insurer apart from paperwork. However, tiny problems may still appear.
Disadvantages of this program include the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes. For example, some mixtures can be used against migraine or hot flashes, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is seen by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while others are not.
Companies have developed in the research and analysis of the data. They must seek permission from the patient before collecting the necessary information from the pharmacy.
From now on, they are forced to do so by the authorities, even if they have not been sanctioned for their failures in the past.
Recently, some companies have also been processing the results of laboratory analyses and linking them with data on drug consumption to provide an even more accurate picture of patients' health status.
More and more companies have access to data, and control of use is becoming increasingly difficult at the same time.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A proposal for a law on the expansion of the circle of control of the authorities concerning companies specializing in the provision of data is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not enough and that is why he has further developed his program, which would condition the transmission of data to the sole agreement of the data subject.
It is another question of whether the person concerned is really free to give his or her consent or not, since if he or she refuses, the insurance does not sign an insurance contract with him or her.
Thus, and ultimately, the hens depend on the fox’s benevolence.
The global menu of Marseille
The European Union and India are doubling their trade.
Since the European Union and India are very important trading partners for each other, this theme also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit alongside the other problems, largely global.
Today, there will also be a France-India summit where cooperation in the field of atomic energy will be discussed.
The European Union recognizes that India is an emerging democratic great power that should be given a broader right to speak in international affairs, but member countries have not yet managed to agree on their support for New Delhi for its candidacy as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
They did not dwell too much on this issue yesterday, at this 9th summit held in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, as well as the current President of the Union, as well as Commission President José Manuel Barroso and the head of diplomacy, Javier Solana, welcomed the Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed that in five years they would double the number of trades, which means an increase of a good hundred billion euros.
Taking into account that between 2000 and 2007, the trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this does not seem to be an over-ambitious goal.
In this sense, they have legally harmonized the 26 bilateral agreements with India on civilian flights, so that air traffic can also grow in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the EU by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy has promised to speed up negotiations.
The aim is to balance the situation with India, which is the EU's main trading partner, and New Delhi, which is only ranked ninth among EU partners.
The summit focused its attention on global affairs.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan was strongly condemned, as well as all forms of terrorism, and the urgency of holding a United Nations conference on this issue was raised.
The completion of the Doha business cycle has also been called for, although both have a large part in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed that it remains faithful to the energy and climate agenda, including that it would like to reduce its releases of toxic materials by at least 20 percent by 2020.
India also agreed on this point, as well as the need for a global market at next year’s climate conference, and to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by fifty percent by 2050.
They would also like to prevent rising food prices, and supported the convening of an international working meeting to discuss the financial crisis.
The head of state of India travels to the French capital today, where during a bilateral meeting, he is preparing to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of atomic energy.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive orders worth 20 billion euros for the construction of Indian atomic reactors.
According to the news agency, the deal will last for 15 years.
